{
  "texts": [
    "This uses the fact that no state from G ′ j has an R ▷ -successor, so our formula ψ, i.e., ♢ ▷ ⊤, that appears in the antecedent of (Split) cannot be true at a state from G ′ j.",
    "Not only does (F G ′ j) ′ validate (Split), but unlike F G ′ j, it also clearly validates ♢ i ψ, i.e., ♢ i ♢ ▷ ⊤.",
    "Thus, by the reasoning at the beginning of this section, the logic of (F G ′ j) ′ is Kripke-frame inconsistent.",
    "It only remains to show that for j ̸ = k, the logics of (F G ′ j) ′ and (F G ′ k) ′ are distinct.",
    "This follows from the fact above thatF G ′ j ⊩ (□ ▷ ⊥ ∧ □ ◁ ⊥) → χ and F G ′ k ⊮ (□ ▷ ⊥ ∧ □ ◁ ⊥) → χ, which implies (F G ′ j) ′ ⊩ (□ ▷ ⊥ ∧ □ ◁ ⊥) → χ and (F G ′ k) ′ ⊮ (□ ▷ ⊥ ∧ □ ◁ ⊥) → χ because χ ∈ L(Φ, {+}) does not contain the □ i modality, and (F G ′ j) ′ and (F G ′ k) ′ differ from F G ′ j and F G ′ k, respectively, only in the accessibility relation for □ i."
  ]
}